author: bridgeheadone
body:
People who rag on growth tech fail to understand the scalability. 

It is not a production line and they don’t need significant capex to grow. It is digital roll out and marketing. Scalability. Profit growth. 

That’s why companies like Adobe, Microsoft, PayPal, Amazon etc can sustain 20% growth yoy with super high margins. They don’t need to hire 4000 workers or buy 600 hydraulic presses to grow to the same extent as an auto manufacturer. Obviously they need to invest, but they can scale soooo much faster and cheaper.

author: Mountain-Dig
body:
I mean, some people are successful day traders. But it's a lot of work to learn about a basket of stocks and learn where they are overbought and oversold.

For example, Adobe is a stock I like on the long side. A couple of weeks ago, it was trading at $450, which is at the low end of its range. I know it will probably revert to closer to $500 shortly. If it doesn't, it has an earnings date coming up in late march which will cause some traders to bid it up in anticipation that the earnings could be good. So I bought a LOT of Adobe at $450.

Today it's trading at $490. That's about an 8% gain in 12 days. I pocketed that, and I'm on to my next play.

I read a lot of stock research and I intimately know the trading patterns of about 100 tickers. It's a lot of work.

author: f1ndnewp
body:
You've entirely missed the point with your "David vs Goliath" posts and "getting back @ wallstreet", and the point was that a bunch of retail investors can make a difference in the market because its what's on the margin that matters and not the absolute numbers.

Furthermore, the entire limiting buys fiasco and removing one star reviews from app stores was a kick in the butt for the young people on here to understand that NEITHER big finance NOR big tech is not their friend, and never has been. That was something very obvious to technically inclined folks back in the 2000s, but big tech prettified their products enough to get todays young people on board.

Nearly everything now is subscription based purely to extract more money from the consumer for little additional utility. E.g. you could actually own Adobe products several years back, now if you want to photoshop anything you better pay that subscription. Shit, you could own your Microsoft Office suite back in 2013. What about now? And the trend is only accelerating.

And its the same story with a lot of the fancy fin-tech products geared towards the younger investor.

author: here_we_gogo
body:
IMHO Fidelity calling them "disruptive" is a bit of a stretch... I think FBOTX is interesting and actually works very well combined with ARKQ. But in general I find a lot of overlap both between F's disruptives, and also with SP500's... plenty of amazon, microsoft, fb, google, uber, nvidia, apple, mastercard, visa, cap one... I'm not saying they are bad funds, but that fidelity calling them "disruptive" is a bit of a marketing plot in my view. 

FINANCE

- FNTEX: capital one, mastercard, signature bank, visa, ally... 

- ARKF: square, mercadolibre, zillow, ice, paypal, sea... 

BROAD

- FGDFX:  uber, google, facebook, amazon, microsoft... 

- FTEKX: google, microsoft, adobe, facebook...

- ARKK: tesla, roku, square, teladoc, nvidia, protolabs. 


COMMUNICATIONS

- FNETX: t-mobile, twitter, facebook, amazon, google, activision, uber, dish...

- ARKW: tesla, roku, square, teladoc, grayscale, spotify...

FPAC (love the managment team)

AACU (new large SPAC, could be a homerun, could be a dud but it's close to NAV)

GCACU (low price, 1/2 warrants, will probably dump after split)

 JOFFU (Fintech focused SPAC with solid managment)

 DLCAU (newer SPAC, 1/2 warrants, management team are ex paypal, ebay, adobe guys, fintech target)

JWSMU (has two other SPACs, one has a DA with Cano Health and trading at almost $15 per share, the other doesn't have a target and still above $11. This is the largest of the three SPACs)

COOLU (1/3 warrants, the head of the SPAC seems like he has a lot of solid connections and lots of experience. This could be a dark horse that doesn't get talked about).

author: mcuban
body:
Supply and Demand, but in this case it literally could be because the source of demand has been crippled . When RH shut it down, then cut it back, lets put aside why, they cut of the greatest source of demand.  They created a RobinHood Dive.  No RH buyers, means sellers lower their price to find buyers. And they keep on lowering it till they find buyers.  Keep the most natural buyers out of the market and the price keeps on FALLING.

Then that drop accelerates because the more the stock falls the more owners who bought on margin get margin calls.  When that margin call happens, its brutal.  They just take your stock, send you a fuck you note and sell your stock at the market price, no matter how low. They just want to get your cash to pay back the loan. 

That then accelerates the selling. 

Which then leads to what we are seeing in the market right now with GME in particular

&#x200B;

So what to do ? 

If you can afford to hold the stock, you hold.  I dont own it, but thats what i would do. 

Why ? because when RH and the other online brokers open it back up to buyers, then we will see what WSB is really made of. That is when you get to make it all work. 

I have no doubt that there are funds and big players that have shorted this stock again thinking they are smarter than everyone on WSB.

I know you are going to hate to hear this, but the lower it goes, the more powerful WSB can be stepping up to buy the stock again. The only question is what broker do you use . Do you stay with RH , who is going to have the same liquidity problems over and over again, or do you as a group find a broker with a far, far, far better balance sheet that wont cut you off and then go ham on Wall Street.

author: mcuban
body:
I learned some expensive lessons when i first started trading stocks.  It was painful. But i tried to learn what i got right and wrong.  Right now, right here. The game is changing.  The hard part is ask yourself if what you believed in has actually changed. 

BTC HODLers are a great example to follow.  Many bought at the highs in 2017 and watched it fall by 2/3 or more.  But they held on because they believed in the asset. 

The same applies to stocks.  When I buy a stock  I make sure i know why Im buying it. Then I HODL until till I learn that something has changed.  THe price may go up or down, but if i still believe in the logic that made me buy the asset, I dont sell. If something changed that I didnt expect , then I look at selling.

author: RenaissanceMan79
body:
>If i borrow a stock from you to short, and when I short it and your buddy buys it, then they can loan it to someone else to short

I finally get it now:

* A loans 1 share to B
* B short sells it to C
* C then loans the share out to D
* D also short sells it

Even though only 1 share is involved the short interest is now 2 because D owes C 1 share, and B owes A 1 share. D could buy and close the short with C, now C has a share that B could buy and close with A and the whole thing is unwound.

Only problem is D sold the share to WSB... and WE AREN'T SELLING!!! 💎🙌

I find SQ is solid, SHOP as well. I got in early on those, though. I got sucked into the WSB and GME fiasco until I realized this sub existed. This is a lot more... calm, lol.

Anyways. I’ve found the tech stocks to be fruitful and I’m a big believer in the disruption and adoption, with that being said, I looked into what makes the technology, like what’s needed for the hardware, and came across SNPS & TSM, they’re nice long plays as well.

3D printing is something that removes the human component and thus creating more efficiency and yielding cleaner results, if you believe in that industry, which needs time, there are some interesting picks like NNMD, MTLS, Felix, SSYS, PRLB.

body:
I find SQ is solid, SHOP as well. I got in early on those, though. I got sucked into the WSB and GME fiasco until I realized this sub existed. This is a lot more... calm, lol.

Anyways. I’ve found the tech stocks to be fruitful and I’m a big believer in the disruption and adoption, with that being said, I looked into what makes the technology, like what’s needed for the hardware, and came across SNPS & TSM, they’re nice long plays as well.

3D printing is something that removes the human component and thus creating more efficiency and yielding cleaner results, if you believe in that industry, which needs time, there are some interesting picks like NNMD, MTLS, Felix, SSYS, PRLB.

author: wiifan55
body: The restricted access is a result of liquidity issues by the app brokers, not pressure from the hedge funds. I mean, sure there's no real way to disprove the latter isn't at play too. But liquidity offers a perfectly logical explanation for the restricted access. It's like the old saying goes: if you hear hooves when in North America, think horse, not zebra.

author: bored2death2
body: Completely agree with your point.  I \*was\* emotional about the trade, mostly pissed off at myself for not following my rules. I generally don't do covered calls AND when I do I get out of them well before loosing 10x the original sell price.  But I got over it quickly and soon found another thing to get frustrated with myself over.  Sure $ZBRA is a great stock and selling PUTs is a great way to make some scratch...but I didn't avoid their options who has a pretty large gap in the BID/ASK coupled with a low volume? Hard to buy back at times.  And while I didn't loose money - it took me three days to get rid of vertical PUT spread.  Only after I broke up the legs was I able to manage it.
